│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe SLP horizontal reduction for boolean logic      │
│ (select-based and/or) reassociates the reduction and may reorder operands.    │
│ With LLVM's poison semantics, the reduction is not freely associative:        │
│ reordering can expose a previously-gated poison value. In the reproducer, the │
│ original code gates a potentially poison %c1 with condition %1 first (s1 =    │
│ select %1, %c1, false). The vectorizer rewrites it to first gate with %c3     │
│ (select %c3, %c1, false), which can select poison %c1 when %c3 is true even   │
│ if %1 is false, producing a poison result where the original was false. The   │
│ existing freeze of the condition (%c3) is insufficient because the problem is │
│ the early selection of a poison RHS operand (%c1), not a poison               │
│ condition.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The pass detects a horizontal        │
│ reduction and vectorizes it, inserting a freeze on %c3:\n  %2 = freeze i1     │
│ %c3\n  %op.rdx = select i1 %2, i1 %c1, i1 false\n  %op.rdx1 = select i1       │
│ %op.rdx, i1 %1, i1 false\n- Alive2 shows the target becomes poison when %c1   │
│ is poison and %1 is false while %c3 is true. The original is safely false due │
│ to gating by %1.\n- The first transformation point is                         │
│ HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce(), specifically in the helper                │
│ GetNewVectorizedTree (freeze inserted at SLPVectorizer.cpp:19841). The        │
│ analysis information (ReducedValsToOps) is used to choose/swap operands; if   │
│ neither operand was originally used as the select condition, the code freezes │
│ VectorizedTree, which does not prevent the poison leak here.\n\n3. Root Cause │
│ Analysis:\nThe reduction builder may begin combining two values that were     │
│ never used as the select condition (operand 0) in the original scalar chain.  │
│ For boolean logic reductions, this can break the original short-circuit-like  │
│ gating order, allowing a poison RHS value to be selected earlier than in the  │
│ original code. The current fallback of freezing the would-be condition        │
│ (VectorizedTree) in that case does not fix the semantic issue because the     │
│ selected RHS may still be poison and is now reachable before the original     │
│ guard. We must ensure we start the reduction from a value that was originally │
│ used as a condition (operand 0) to preserve gating order, or avoid            │
│ vectorizing otherwise.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe add a reordering     │
│ step immediately after forming the Candidates list for a reduction chunk      │
│ (right after handling shuffled extracts, before the constant/threshold        │
│ checks). For boolean logic reductions (AnyBoolLogicOp), we stable-partition   │
│ Candidates so that values that were used as the select condition (operand 0)  │
│ in any of the original reduction operations are placed first. We determine    │
│ this by consulting ReducedValsToOps and checking getRdxOperand(I,0) for       │
│ isBoolLogicOp(I). This ensures the first combine(s) start from a safe LHS     │
│ that preserves the original gating order, preventing the early exposure of    │
│ poison from RHS-only values. The code keeps the relative order within each    │
│ partition, minimizing perturbation.\n\nWe insert the following block at line  │
│ ~19933 (immediately after the shuffled-extracts handling):\n- Compute         │
│ IsLHSInBoolOp(V) using ReducedValsToOps and getRdxOperand(I,0).\n- Partition  │
│ Candidates into LHSFirst and Others; if both sets are non-empty, rebuild      │
│ Candidates with LHSFirst followed by Others.\n\nThis change is minimal and    │
│ localized, does not alter non-boolean reductions, and leverages the existing  │
│ analysis data structures.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems from starting a    │
│ boolean logic reduction with two RHS-only values, which can select poison     │
│ earlier than the original gated order. By reordering boolean reduction        │
│ candidates to start from values that originally served as select conditions   │
│ (operand 0), we preserve the gating order and avoid the poison leak. The      │
│ inserted stable reordering uses the already-maintained ReducedValsToOps and   │
│ helper predicates, and should fix the reproducer while keeping other          │
│ reductions unaffected."})                                                     │
