│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The slp-vectorizer horizontally reduces a chain of boolean logic selects      │
│ (logical and/or encoded as select patterns). It reassociates and may reorder  │
│ operands. With LLVM poison semantics, this is not freely associative:         │
│ reordering can expose a previously gated poison value. In the reproducer, the │
│ original scalar sequence gates a potentially poison %c1 using %1 first (s1 =  │
│ select %1, %c1, false). The vectorizer reorders so it first gates %c1 with    │
│ %c3 (select %c3, %c1, false). If %c1 is poison, %1 is false, and %c3 is true, │
│ the transformed code selects poison, while the original returned false. This  │
│ is reported by Alive2 as "Target is more poisonous than source".              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The pass identifies a horizontal reduction and vectorizes it. It introduces │
│ a freeze on %c3:                                                              │
│   %2 = freeze i1 %c3                                                          │
│   %op.rdx = select i1 %2, i1 %c1, i1 false                                    │
│   %op.rdx1 = select i1 %op.rdx, i1 %1, i1 false                               │
│ - Alive2 shows the target produces poison when %c1 is poison and %1=false,    │
│ %c3=true. The original yields false since %1 was the initial guard.           │
│ - The first transformation point is HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce(). The   │
│ helper GetNewVectorizedTree at lines ~19819–19847 attempts to pick which      │
│ operand to feed as LHS for boolean reductions, using ReducedValsToOps and a   │
│ fallback freeze of VectorizedTree. That freeze is only on the condition-like  │
│ operand, not on the RHS; thus it doesn't prevent poison leaking when the      │
│ order makes a RHS-only candidate selected early.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ - For boolean logic reductions (select-based logical and/or), the             │
│ short-circuit-like gating order matters for poison safety. The current        │
│ algorithm may begin combining two values that were never used as the select   │
│ condition (operand 0) in any original scalar op. This can select a previously │
│ gated poison RHS earlier than in the original program.                        │
│ - The current freeze logic in GetNewVectorizedTree is insufficient because    │
│ freezing the would-be condition doesn't stop the RHS from being selected      │
│ early.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                       │
│ - Insertion point: line 19933 (immediately after the shuffled-extracts block  │
│ and before the "Emit code for constant values" section within                 │
│ HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce()).                                          │
│ - Change: Stable-reorder the local Candidates vector for boolean logic        │
│ reductions so that we start combining from values that originally served as   │
│ the select condition (operand 0) of any boolean logic op. This preserves the  │
│ original gating and prevents early exposure of RHS-only poison values.        │
│ - Suggested code to insert at line 19933:                                     │
│   // Prefer starting boolean logic reductions from values that originally     │
│   // appeared as the select condition (operand 0). This preserves the         │
│   // short-circuit gating order and avoids exposing poison from RHS-only      │
│   // operands when we reassociate the reduction.                              │
│   if (AnyBoolLogicOp && Candidates.size() > 1) {                              │
│     auto IsLHSInBoolOp = [&](Value *V) {                                      │
│       auto It = ReducedValsToOps.find(V);                                     │
│       if (It == ReducedValsToOps.end())                                       │
│         return false;                                                         │
│       return any_of(It->second, [&](Instruction *I) {                         │
│         return isBoolLogicOp(I) && getRdxOperand(I, /*Index=*/0) == V;        │
