  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe slp-vectorizer horizontally
reduces a chain of boolean logic selects (logical and/or encoded as select
patterns). It reassociates and may reorder operands. With LLVM poison semantics,
this is not freely associative: reordering can expose a previously gated poison
value. In the reproducer, the original scalar sequence gates a potentially poison
%c1 using %1 first (s1 = select %1, %c1, false). The vectorizer reorders so it
first gates %c1 with %c3 (select %c3, %c1, false). If %c1 is poison, %1 is false,
and %c3 is true, the transformed code selects poison, while the original returned
false. This is reported by Alive2 as \"Target is more poisonous than
source\".\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The pass identifies a horizontal
reduction and vectorizes it. It introduces a freeze on %c3:\n  %2 = freeze i1
%c3\n  %op.rdx = select i1 %2, i1 %c1, i1 false\n  %op.rdx1 = select i1 %op.rdx,
i1 %1, i1 false\n- Alive2 shows the target produces poison when %c1 is poison and
%1=false, %c3=true. The original yields false since %1 was the initial guard.\n-
The first transformation point is HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce(). The helper
GetNewVectorizedTree at lines ~19819\u201319847 attempts to pick which operand to
feed as LHS for boolean reductions, using ReducedValsToOps and a fallback freeze
of VectorizedTree. That freeze is only on the condition-like operand, not on the
RHS; thus it doesn't prevent poison leaking when the order makes a RHS-only
candidate selected early.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- For boolean logic
reductions (select-based logical and/or), the short-circuit-like gating order
matters for poison safety. The current algorithm may begin combining two values
that were never used as the select condition (operand 0) in any original scalar
op. This can select a previously gated poison RHS earlier than in the original
program.\n- The current freeze logic in GetNewVectorizedTree is insufficient
because freezing the would-be condition doesn't stop the RHS from being selected
early.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Insertion point: line 19933
(immediately after the shuffled-extracts block and before the \"Emit code for
constant values\" section within HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce()).\n- Change:
Stable-reorder the local Candidates vector for boolean logic reductions so that
we start combining from values that originally served as the select condition
(operand 0) of any boolean logic op. This preserves the original gating and
prevents early exposure of RHS-only poison values.\n- Suggested code to insert at
line 19933:\n  // Prefer starting boolean logic reductions from values that
originally\n  // appeared as the select condition (operand 0). This preserves
the\n  // short-circuit gating order and avoids exposing poison from RHS-only\n
// operands when we reassociate the reduction.\n  if (AnyBoolLogicOp &&
Candidates.size() > 1) {\n    auto IsLHSInBoolOp = [&](Value *V) {\n      auto It
= ReducedValsToOps.find(V);\n      if (It == ReducedValsToOps.end())\n
return false;\n      return any_of(It->second, [&](Instruction *I) {\n
return isBoolLogicOp(I) && getRdxOperand(I, /*Index=*/0) == V;\n      });\n
};\n    SmallVector<Value *> LHSFirst, Others;\n
LHSFirst.reserve(Candidates.size());\n    Others.reserve(Candidates.size());\n
for (Value *V : Candidates)\n      (IsLHSInBoolOp(V) ? LHSFirst :
Others).push_back(V);\n    // Only reorder if both partitions are non-empty.\n
if (!LHSFirst.empty() && LHSFirst.size() != Candidates.size()) {\n
SmallVector<Value *> NewOrder;\n      NewOrder.reserve(Candidates.size());\n
NewOrder.append(LHSFirst.begin(), LHSFirst.end());\n
NewOrder.append(Others.begin(), Others.end());\n
Candidates.swap(NewOrder);\n    }\n  }\n\nThis leverages the existing
ReducedValsToOps map and helper predicates isBoolLogicOp/getRdxOperand(). It is a
local, minimal change that only touches the boolean logic path.\n\nAlternative
considered but not chosen: Freeze both operands when creating boolean reductions.
This is safe but over-conservative and may pessimize codegen.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe bug is due to operand reordering in boolean logic horizontal
reductions, which can violate poison-safe gating. The fix is to bias the
candidate order for boolean reductions to start from values used as select
conditions (operand 0) in the original code, preserving the gating order and
avoiding the poison leak. This should make the transformed IR poison-safe and fix
the provided reproducer without impacting non-boolean reductions.",
